SIMPLE: magnanimous
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Magnanimous
<hw>Mag*nan"i*mous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos><ety>[L.
<ets>magnanimus</ets>; <ets>magnus</ets> great + <ets>animus</ets> mind.
See <er>Magnate</er>, and <er>Animus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Great
of mind; elevated in soul or in sentiment; raised above what is low,
mean, or ungenerous; of lofty and courageous spirit; <as>as, a
<ex>magnanimous</ex> character; a <ex>magnanimous</ex>
conqueror.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be <qex>magnanimous</qex> in the enterprise.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To give a kingdom hath been thought⟦br⟧
Greater and nobler done, and to lay down⟦br⟧
Far more <qex>magnanimous</qex> than to assume.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Dictated by or exhibiting nobleness of soul;
honorable; noble; not selfish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Both strived for death; <qex>magnanimous</qex> debate.</q>
<rj><qau>Stirling.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is an indissoluble union between a <qex>magnanimous</qex>
policy and the solid rewards of public prosperity and felicity.</q>
<rj><qau>Washington.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Magnanimously</ent>⟦br⟧
